WE PROPOSE TO ADDRESS THE PROBLEM OF DETERMINING THE STAR FORMATION CHARACTERISTICS OF CLUSTERED OBJECTS IN BLENDED OR UNRESOLVED REGIONS BY COMBINING OUR LARGE LIBRARY OF YSO SED MODELS WITH ALGORITHMS THAT SIMULTANEOUSLY FIT MULTIPLE WAVELENGTH INFRARED PHOTOMETRIC DATASETS. OUR RESEARCH FOCUSES ON THE LUMINOSITY FUNCTION AND RELATED PARAMETERS OF YOUNG STARS IN FIVE DIFFERENT, REPRESENTATIVE, GIANT MOLECULAR CLOUDS, EACH WITH MULTIPLE SITES OF MASSIVE CLUSTERED, BLENDED ACTIVITY. OUR GOAL IS TO MEASURE THE DEMOGRAPHICS OF ALL THE SITES OF CLUSTERED STAR FORMATION SMALLER THAN ABOUT 1 PC IN DIAMETER (DEPENDING ON DISTANCE) -- THAT IS, THOSE FOR WHICH THE BEAMSIZES OF FAR INFRARED PHOTOMETRY DATASETS DO NOT RESOLVE THE INDIVIDUAL STARS -- TO EXTRACT THEIR LUMINOSITY FUNCTIONS, AND TO ENABLE COMPARATIVE IMF STUDIES. ALTHOUGH THE ARCHIVAL IMAGES WERE OBTAINED AT MULTIPLE INFRARED WAVELENGTHS AND WITH INSTRUMENTS OF VERY DIVERSE BEAMSIZES, WE WILL USE OUR SED MODELS AND ALGORITHMS TO FIND THE MOST-PROBABLE SET OF INFRARED LUMINOSITIES FOR EACH CLUSTER. ALL THE REGIONS HAVE BEEN SURVEYED AND ARCHIVED BY SPITZER, MIPS AND IRAC, WITH ANCILLARY DATA WELL IN IRAS, MSX AND 2MASS. OUR STRATEGY IS BASED ON APPLYING OUR ROBITAILLE-WHITNEY SED MODEL DATABASE TO THE OBSERVATIONS. TO ENSURE THE MOST WIDE-SPREAD SUBSEQUENT USE OF OUR TOOLS, WE PROPOSE TO DEVELOP THEM WITH FLEXIBLE VIRTUAL OBSERVATORY (VO)-COMPLIANT INTERFACES. THE TOOLS WILL INCORPORATE THE MODELING PARAMETERS, PHYSICAL CONSTRAINTS (IMF, ETC) AND BEST-FITS TO HANDLE MULTIPLE INFRARED DATASETS, BOTH MOSAIC AND CATALOG DATA. THE TOOLS WILL USE THE MODELS TO EXTRAPOLATE THE SEDS OF THE DISTINCT COMPONENTS IN THE CLUSTER, AND THEN TO CALCULATE THE MOST LIKELY SIMULTANEOUS SET OF SEDS FOR THE SET OF SOURCES. ALTHOUGH TYPICALLY THE DIFFERENT BEAMSIZES OF THE DATASETS AND THE BLENDING OF MULTIPLE SOURCES WITHIN A BEAM MAKE FINDING A UNIQUE SOLUTION DIFFICULT, OUR PACKAGES WOULD EXTRACT THE MOST-PROBABLE ENSEMBLE OF SEDS, WEIGHTING THE RESULTS BY ADJUSTABLE PARAMETERS, FOR EXAMPLE THE ASSUMED IMF OR AGE. ULTIMATELY THE MODELS THEMSELVES WILL BE IMPROVED. WE WILL TAKE ADVANTAGE OF SUBMM AND OTHER DATASETS WHEN AVAILABLE. THE FIVE SITES FOR STUDY ARE W43, W49, W51, CYGNUS-X, AND VELA MOLECULAR RIDGE D, CONTAINING ABOUT 50 MASSIVE CLUSTERS. THEIR DISTANCES RANGE FROM 700PC TO 11 KPC, WHILE THEIR POPULATIONS EMPHASIZE STELLAR MASSES FROM THE INTERMEDIATE TO THE VERY MASSIVE. THE PROBLEM OF STUDYING UNRESOLVED SOURCES IN MIXED DATASETS IS A GENERAL ONE. MANY MORE REGIONS OF DENSELY CLUSTERED STAR FORMATION, OR BLENDED REGIONS OF OTHER KINDS, CAN BE STUDIED WITH THE FLEXIBLE TOOLS WE PROPOSE TO DEVELOP; WE HAVE SELECTED THE ABOVE PROJECT BECAUSE OF OUR SCIENTIFIC INTERESTS AND THE RANGE OF CONDITIONS THAT THE MOLECULAR CLOUDS SPAN. ALTHOUGH WE WILL DESIGN OUR ALGORITHMS AND VO-TOOLS FOR THIS PARTICULAR APPLICATION, WE EXPECT THAT THEY WILL FIND WIDE USE IN OTHER KINDS OF PROBLEMS.

WE PROPOSE TO DEVELOP AND TEST AN EXTENDED RANGE, VARIABLE PULSE-RATE, LASER ALTIMETER THAT WILL BE ABLE TO MEASURE THE TIDAL DISTORTION OF EUROPA AND OBTAIN HIGH ACCURACY TOPOGRAPHIC DATA ON A SURFACE TRACK OF OVER 155 DEGREES ON A TYPICAL FLYBY. THE INSTRUMENT WILL BE ABLE TO RANGE TO THE SURFACE OF EUROPA FROM 25-KM TO OVER 4000-KM ALTITUDE. WITH THE TRACK COVERAGE PROVIDED BY THE EXTENDED RANGE ALTIMETER THE SHAPE OF EUROPA, INCLUDING THE COMBINED CONTRIBUTIONS FROM THE ROTATIONAL FLATTENING, THE TOPOGRAPHY, AND THE TEMPORALLY AND SPATIALLY VARIABLE RADIAL TIDAL DISTORTION WILL BE DETECTABLE. THE INSTRUMENT WILL BE A MODIFICATION OF THE PRESENTLY OPERATING, AND HIGHLY SUCCESSFUL, AND SINGLE BEAM MERCURY LASER ALTIMETER (MLA) ON THE MESSENGER DISCOVERY MISSION. THE MLA LASER OPERATES AT 8 HZ AT MERCURY AND HAS SUCCESSFULLY RANGED FROM OVER 1600 KM TO THE MERCURY SURFACE. ALLOWING FOR THE 6 TO 1 DIFFERENCE IN GEOMETRIC ALBEDO (0.106 TO 0.67) THE RANGE AT EUROPA BY MLA WOULD BE 4300 KM AND, WITH IMPROVED RECEIVER ELECTRONICS THAT WE ANTICIPATE DEMONSTRATING AS PART OF THIS PROPOSAL, THE RANGE COULD BE SIGNIFICANTLY GREATER. THE PRIMARY OBJECTIVE OF THIS PROPOSAL IS TO TEST THE AUTONOMOUS VARIABLE PULSE-RATE LASER BY MODIFYING THE SPARE MLA ENGINEERING TEST UNIT (ETU) LASER TRANSMITTER. THIS MODIFICATION WILL INCREASE THE OUTPUT ENERGY OF THE LASER BY ~20% AND ENABLE A MAXIMUM FIRE RATE OF ~50 HZ AND REDUCED PULSE ENERGY UNDER THE SAME ELECTRICAL POWER FOR CLOSEST APPROACH OPERATIONS, WHICH WILL BRING A FOUR-FOLD INCREASE IN THE NUMBER OF LASER SHOTS TO BE COLLECTED OVER EACH FLYBY, COMPARED TO THE CURRENT MLA DESIGN. THE INCLUSION OF A LONG-RANGE LASER ALTIMETER CAPABLE OF MEASURING TOPOGRAPHIC PROFILES AND DETERMINING EUROPAS BODY TIDE WILL SIGNIFICANTLY INCREASE THE SCIENTIFIC VALUE AND CAPABILITY OF THE CLIPPER MISSION.
